Consider seeing a women's health physio for stress incontinence symptoms.
Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: ClinicalExamComment
Comment Value: None

Women's Health Recommendations: -Screening is important. Visit a general practitioner for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: ClinicalExamComment
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Women's Health Recommendations: -Screening is important. Visit a general practitioner for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: ClinicalExamComment
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Women's Health Recommendations: Visit a general practitioner or a gynaecologists for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Consider seeing a women's health physio for stress incontinence symptoms.
Overview Notes: Supplement with vitamin D3 5000iu daily. Recheck levels in 3 to 6 months aiming for a level of 50 to 80ng/ml.

Men's Health Recommendations: 
Women's Health Recommendations: Visit a general practitioner or a gynaecologists for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Consider seeing a women's health physio for stress incontinence symptoms.
Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: ClinicalExamNote
Comment Value: Eczema/ dryness around nose
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: ClinicalExamRecommendation
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Women's Health Recommendations: -Screening is important. Visit a general practitioner for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Overview Notes: Supplement with vitamin D3 5000iu daily. Recheck levels in 3 to 6 months aiming for a level of 50 to 80ng/ml.

Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: LabTestNote
Comment Value: Mildly increased urea, most likely due to dehydration. Decreased haemoglobin, microcytic hypochromic anaemia noted, possible iron deficiency or thalassaemia trait
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Overview Notes: Supplement with vitamin D3 5000iu daily. Recheck levels in 3 to 6 months aiming for a level of 50 to 80ng/ml.

Overview Notes: Raised urea most likely due to dehydration. Make sure you are drinking enough water during the day. Understandably your bloods were done fasting which accounts for this. I am not concerned.
Comment Key: MedicalHistoryNote
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Comment Value: -You have a Thalassemia trait. This means that your red blood cells are smaller than usual but they still function as they should.
-Continue annual medical screening & employ lifestyle habits that benefit your present & future self.
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Employee: Amina Pahad
Report Date: 2020-02-14
Doctor: Christie Pilossof
Nurse: Lebo Cindi
Clinical Recommendations: 
Men's Health Recommendations: 
Women's Health Recommendations: Visit a general practitioner or a gynaecologists for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Consider seeing a women's health physio for stress incontinence symptoms.
Overview Notes: Supplement with vitamin D3 5000iu daily. Recheck levels in 3 to 6 months aiming for a level of 50 to 80ng/ml.

Nurse: Lebo Cindi
Clinical Recommendations: 
Men's Health Recommendations: 
Women's Health Recommendations: -Screening is important. Visit a general practitioner for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.

Women's Health Recommendations: -Screening is important. Visit a general practitioner for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Overview Notes: Further testing required to investigate the cause of your anaemia. Recommend iron studies and ferritin levels and a Thalassaemia screen. Please follow up with one of our team to do this or see your regular GP. It's very important to establish the cause.
Comment Key: MensHealthRecommendation
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Comment Key: MentalHealthAnxietyRecommendation
Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Overview Notes: Supplement with vitamin D3 5000iu daily. Recheck levels in 3 to 6 months aiming for a level of 50 to 80ng/ml.
Comment Key: MentalHealthNote

Doctor: Christie Pilossof
Nurse: Lebo Cindi
Clinical Recommendations: 
Men's Health Recommendations: 
Women's Health Recommendations: Visit a general practitioner or a gynaecologists for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Consider seeing a women's health physio for stress incontinence symptoms.
Overview Notes: Pay attention to stress management. It's great that you do yoga. You can also consider breathing exercises and meditation. Try the apps available to support these practices, we like headspace and insight timer.

Comment Value: None
Special Investigation Notes: All normal

Overview Notes: Pay attention to stress management. It's great that you do yoga. You can also consider breathing exercises and meditation. Try the apps available to support these practices, we like headspace and insight timer.

Women's Health Recommendations: -Screening is important. Visit a general practitioner for a Pap smear and a Radiologist for a mammogram.
Overview Notes: Raised urea most likely due to dehydration. Make sure you are drinking enough water during the day. Understandably your bloods were done fasting which accounts for this. I am not concerned.
